Literary Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton — this summer, literary fans around the world held celebrations in various arts festivals and bookstores to commemorate the 20th anniversary of J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series, the first book of which is Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone (originally titled Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone in some regions). They had ample reason to do so.
Since 1997, when this young wizard first appeared on June 26, the "boy who lived" has become a symbol of resilience and tenacity.
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, has been translated into more than 70 languages, and has sold a cumulative total of 450 million copies.
The Harry Potter films, based on this book, have collectively earned $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed merchandise has generated another $7 billion in revenue.
For readers of a certain age and with literary sensibilities, it's hard to imagine a time when the world wasn't under the spell of Rowling's writings.
Therefore, I'm constantly amazed by my students' poor reaction to Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone in the fall of 1999, when I first included the book in my popular literature course at Princeton University. I've been teaching the "Best Sellers in America" series since 1993.
This course explores popular works from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to ponder why and how these bestsellers have captivated their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask students to choose a final book that represents popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year the Potter craze fiercely swept America's shores.
In June, the American publisher of this series rushed the hardcover edition of the second Harry Potter novel, Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets, into bookstores.
The organization also published the third installment in the series, Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban, on September 8, along with the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone.
By the end of the month, Rowling's novel had swept the top three spots on The New York Times bestseller list, while the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone had taken the top spot on the paperback bestseller list.
The Time magazine even put a bespectacled wizard on its cover.
The image of Harry Potter was ubiquitous everywhere.
My students are eager to know just what drove such a frenzy.
Good heavens, they were thoroughly disappointed.
In their eyes, the Harry Potter series was nothing more than second-rate nonsense, hardly worthy of standing alongside the cherished children's classics like The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings that they remembered from their childhood.
Although their childhood was barely over a few years ago, they condemned Harry Potter in the same manner as many notorious adult critics: "fabricated," "poor writing," "hackneyed," and "tedious."
In June, the American publisher of the series rushed the hardcover edition of the second Harry Potter novel, Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets, into bookstores.
In their eyes, Harry Potter lacked both magic and warmth.
The students' indifference surprised me at the time, but looking back, it wasn't really worth getting so worked up about.
Although adults constituted a significant portion of the Harry Potter audience from the very beginning, these students were precisely at the age where they were incapable of objectively recognizing the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They had outgrown the age for accepting new children's literature, but were still too young to have their own children (I had just had my own child at the time), and they were eager to insist that despite Harry's current popularity, he would soon be forgotten.
In the fall of 2000, the next batch of students also chose "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" as their final analysis book, just like their peers before them, they confidently rejected the work.
Let's fast forward to spring 2007.
After several years of shelving the course, I once again taught "America's Bestselling Books".
When students chose their final analysis book, they chose "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone".
And I am ready to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This is a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who were not university students when they first read Rowling's work but rather teenagers in their early teens, just entering the stage of adolescence. This means they grew up together with Harry, Ron, and Hermione.
The same phenomenon happened again in the autumn of 2010.
For these students, "we grew up with Harry Potter" has become a motto, not a label.
Will Harry be forgotten?
As long as we're still alive, it's impossible.
Since the year 2010, I have taught several bestseller courses, and in both instances, the students chose to review non-Harry Potter novels for their final essays.
Are they tired of Potter?
Based on the summaries, historical translations of proper nouns, preceding texts, and relevant instances, the translation of the current Chinese source sentence into English is:
Now, I choose to include a Harry Potter novel in the curriculum, but I did not choose Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone; instead, I selected Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban – this is my favorite in the Harry Potter series, marking the transition from children's literature to young adult fiction, with complex descriptions of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also love this book.
But how long can the Harry Potter series maintain its popularity?
Each time I teach children's literature, I conduct a survey first: "Which books on the curriculum did you read in your childhood?"
In the year 2010, 86% of people had read Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban.
In the year 2012, this number rose to 94%.
However, the percentages then continued to decline over the years — 87% in 2014, and down to 81% in 2016.
These are all just gut feelings, I know.
However, I'm curious: will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter be below 80% when I teach Childrens literature again next spring?
Will the facts prove that the students of 1999 to 2000 were right, with Harry Potter's status constantly declining, and never becoming an eternal classic?
There still seems to be a tipping point ahead, where the percentage will stabilize and no longer decline?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I was always happy to have him join my classroom.
